@NODE "intro" "WiiLoader - Introduction"
@PREV "main"
@NEXT "req"

 @{b}@{u}Introduction@{uu}@{ub}

 WiiLoader is a small utility to load .dol and .elf-files over network to the Homebrew Channel.
 on a 'patched' Nintendo Wii-console.
 This is handy becuase you don't need to take out and copy applications to the SD-card and
 then insert it in the Wii again to be able to start an application.

 Just select the file and press send, and voila! the application is started =)

 There are similar programs on Windows and Mac, but no program on MorphOS (Amiga).
 So to not be forced to start a wintel-machine to transfer files to the Wii,
 I created a native application todo the work ;)

@ENDNODE

@NODE "req" "WiiLoader - Requirements"
@PREV "intro"
@NEXT "install"

 @{b}@{u}Requirements@{uu}@{ub}

 This program needs at least following stuff:

 · MorphOS 1.x, AmigaOS 4.x or AROS (x86)
 · Magic User Interface (MUI).

@ENDNODE

@NODE "install" "WiiLoader - Installation"
@PREV "req"
@NEXT "usage"

 @{b}@{u}Installation@{uu}@{ub}

 This program doesn't need any installation and because of that doesn't come with
 any form of installer script. Just place it where you want and run it from there! =)
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE "usage" "WiiLoader - Usage"
@PREV "install"
@NEXT "faq"

 @{b}@{u}Usage@{uu}@{ub}

 This program consist of a small user interface, which only has a couple of options.

 @{b}Wii Address@{ub}

   Here you enter the IP-address to you Wii-console.
   You can find it in Homebrew Channel by pressing the home-button.


 @{b}Port@{ub}

   This is the port used for the transfer, normaly this value shouldn't be change
   so the standard value here is 4299.


 @{b}Filename@{ub}

   This is where you enter/selects the file that shall be transfered to the Wii-console.
   Note that it has to be either .dol or .elf-files that can be recognised by Homebrew Channel.

   Check out following URL for a lot of cool homebrew applications :

   http://www.wiibrew.org/


 @{b}Button - Send File@{ub}

   Not much to say here except that this is where the action happens =)
   If you selected correct file, address and port you should be able to se
   the progress bar work while the file is transfered.


 That's all folks! =)

@ENDNODE

@NODE "faq" "WiiLoader - FAQ"
@PREV "usageprefs"
@NEXT "news"

@{b}@{u}FAQ - Frequently Asked Question@{uu}@{ub}

* @{b}Q = Question@{ub}
* @{b}A = Answer@{ub}

------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Q - Why do I get "Could not connect to address" even if I use the correct one?

A - First check if the port number is correct (shall be 4299 normaly),
    then check on the Homebrew Channel that network is actually activated
    by pressing the home-button.
    If that doesn't indicate any problem, think about if you have some
    kind of nasty firewall or router that might causes the problems.

==============================================================================

Q - When the transfer is done, homebrew channel complains about some errors ?

A - First control that the file is actual compatible .ELF or .DOL-file.
    There can be some old .elf-files that might be incompatible with HBC.
    You can try to use a tool called ELF2DOL incase that can help you.

==============================================================================

Q - Why do WiiLoader refuse to start on my MorphOS-system ?

A - WiiLoader uses the new AboutBox-mcc on MorphOS-systems, if you have 2.x
    it's allready there. If you still using 1.4 please use the latest update
    pack if you havn't allready and you'll be able to use WiiLoader again =)

    http://www.morphos-team.net/downloads.html
------------------------------------------------------------------------------ 


@ENDNODE

@NODE "news" "WiiLoader - What's new?"
@PREV "usage"
@NEXT "history"

 @{b}@{u}What's new@{uu}@{ub}

 · Native AROS-version - Yeah!
 · WiiLoader can now be used as a Default Tool to be able to upload the file at once.
 · Changed the connection timeout drastically ;)
 · Cosmetical changes in the GUI while transfers is active.
 · Program now saves the current last settings to ENV: and not ENVARC:
 · Settings are now saved to ENVARC only when Snaphoot is selected in settings menu.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "history" "WiiLoader - History"
@PREV "news"
@NEXT "future"

 @{b}@{u}History@{uu}@{ub}

 · 05-Feb-2009 - Second release (v1.1)

   - Native AROS-version - Yeah!
   - WiiLoader can now be used as a Default Tool to be able to upload the file at once.
   - Changed the connection timeout drastically ;)
   - Cosmetical changes in the GUI while transfers is active.
   - Program now saves the current last settings to ENV: and not ENVARC:
   - Settings are now saved to ENVARC only when Snaphoot is selected in settings menu.

 · 20-Jan-2009 - First release (v1.0)

   - MorphOS native version.
   - AmigaOS4 native version (Thanks to Daniel Westerberg)

@ENDNODE

